06322nam a22008415i 9780812294415DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122944157 a10.9783/97808122944152doi  a(DE-B1597)493765  a(OCoLC)1011109581  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306.83223  aLB 410002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90550:77200aReconnecting State and Kinship /ced. by Tatjana Thelen, Erdmute Alber. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tReconnecting State and Kinship: Temporalities, Scales, Classifications -- tPart I. Traveling Concepts Temporalities, Scales, and the Making of Political Order -- tChapter 1. Corruption as Political Incest -- tChapter 2. Kinship Weaponized -- tChapter 3. Inside and Outside the Language of Kinship -- tChapter 4. Appropriate Kinship, Legitimate Nationhood -- tChapter 5. From Familial to Familiar -- tPart II. Classifying Kinship and the Making of Citizens -- tChapter 6. The Politics of “See-Through” Kinship -- tChapter 7. Undoing Kinship -- tChapter 8. Producing “Good” Families and Citizens in Danish Child Care Institutions -- tChapter 9. After Citizenship -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithin the social sciences, kinship and statehood are often seen as two distinct modes of social organization, sometimes conceived of as following each other in a temporal line and sometimes as operating on different scales. Kinship is traditionally associated with small-scale communities in stateless societies. The state, meanwhile, is viewed as a development away from kinship as political order toward rational, impersonal, and functional forms of rule. In recent decades, theoretical and empirical scholarship has challenged these notions, but the underlying presumption of a deep-rooted opposition between kinship and the (modern) state has remained surprisingly stable.That this binary is so deeply engrained in Western self-understanding and knowledge production poses a considerable challenge to decoding their coproduction. Reconnecting State and Kinship seeks to trace the historical shifts and boundary work implied in the ongoing reproduction of these supposedly discrete or even opposing units of analysis. Contributors ask whether concepts associated with one sphere —including corruption, patronage, lineage, and incest—surface in the other. Policies and interventions modeled upon the assumed polarity can have lasting consequences for mechanisms of marginalization and exclusion, including decisions about life and death.Reconnecting State and Kinship not only explores the boundary-related and classificatory practices that reinforce the kinship/statehood binary but also tracks the traveling of these concepts and their underlying norms through time and space ultimately demonstrating the ways that kinship and "the state" are intertwined.Contributors: Erdmute Alber, Apostolos Andrikopoulos, Helle Bundgaard, Jeanette Edwards, Karen Fog Olwig, Victoria Goddard, Michael Herzfeld, Eirini Papadaki, Frances Pine, Ivan Rajković, Tatjana Thelen, Thomas Zitelmann.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.1 aAlber, Erdmute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlber, Erdmute, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAndrikopoulos, Apostolos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundgaard, Helle, econtributor.4